# Phase 8 (Revision 2)
## Commit Lifecycle Classification & Industry Best Practices

> This document extends the existing Phase 8 implementation.
> Existing functionality must remain intact unless explicitly stated otherwise.

---

# Objective

Enhance Release Commit Validation by introducing intelligent commit lifecycle analysis.

Instead of classifying commits only as "OK" or "Violation", the system shall determine the actual lifecycle state of every commit using Git history analysis.

This will significantly reduce false positives and provide much more meaningful release governance.

---

# FR-31 Commit Lifecycle Analysis

The system shall analyze every commit collected during Release Validation.

Each commit shall be classified into one of the lifecycle states defined below.

---

# FR-32 Commit States

Instead of showing only:

- OK
- Violation

Introduce the following states.

### State 1

OK

Meaning

Valid release commit.

Commit exists.

No issue detected.

---

### State 2

Missing In Release

Meaning

Commit exists on Main.

Expected for Release.

Missing from Release Branch.

Action

Violation.

---

### State 3

Reverted

Meaning

The original commit was introduced into the Release Branch but was later reverted using Git Revert.

This shall NOT be displayed as a normal violation.

Instead display

Status

Reverted

Reason

Commit intentionally reverted from Release Branch.

---

### State 4

Cherry Picked

Meaning

Commit exists through Cherry Pick.

Different SHA may exist.

Equivalent code exists.

Not a violation.

---

### State 5

Direct Release Commit

Meaning

Developer committed directly into Release Branch.

Highlight separately.

---

### State 6

Unknown

Meaning

Unable to confidently determine lifecycle.

Requires Manual Verification.

---

# FR-33 Revert Detection

The implementation shall detect Git Revert operations.

Review GitHub and Git documentation.

Possible detection techniques include:

- Standard "Revert" commit messages.
- References to reverted commit SHA.
- Parent commit relationships.
- Patch comparison where applicable.

The implementation shall not rely only on commit message text.

If possible,

also verify through Git history relationships.

---

# FR-34 Revert Classification

If

Commit A

↓

Later

Revert Commit B

↓

Successfully reverses Commit A

Then

Commit A

Status

Reverted

Commit B

Status

Revert Operation

The UI shall clearly indicate that the original change has already been reverted.

This should not appear as an active violation.

---

# FR-35 Commit Status Priority

Display priority shall follow:

Reverted

↓

Missing In Release

↓

Direct Release Commit

↓

Cherry Picked

↓

OK

↓

Unknown

